Interest Rates are Historically Low
If you=E2=80=99ve been reading Not Boring, or watching the markets, or even=
 turned on the news at some point over the past year, this one should not c=
ome as a surprise to you. Interest rates are historically low, which has dr=
iven up the price of growth assets and forced investors to look for returns=
 in riskier assets.=C2=A0
For most of recent history, investing in Treasuries was essentially free mo=
ney. On the day I was born in 1987, the 10 Year Treasury yield, referred to=
 as the =E2=80=9Crisk-free=E2=80=9D rate because of the infinitesimally sma=
ll chance that the US defaults on its debts, was 7.17%. Inflation that year=
 averaged 4.43%. That meant that you could invest, with practically no risk=
, and have money with 2.74% more buying power the next year.=C2=A0
Take a look at the historical chart of 10 Year Treasury yields versus infla=
tion. Any time the blue line was higher than the red line, you could park y=
our money in bonds and outpace inflation. It wasn=E2=80=99t sexy, and you w=
eren=E2=80=99t going to outperform anyone by doing it, but money=E2=80=99s =
money.=C2=A0
Source: MacroTrends [https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkMuOhiAMRp_mZ6dB8=
MaCxWzmNUyFqmQUDNQxvv2gLiYhNGnTnK_HAOEc4qX3kIjd30DXjtrjmVYkwsiOhHFwVlet6GVT=
K2Z1bau-6ZlLwxQRN3Crpngg249xdQbIBf9scC4atmjRGwFW4NjLXtrKGlU3MLaTaidjxAQvFw7=
r0BvU-IvxCh7ZqheiPX3k10d853eeZ7mBiYEieptKj5S7olZdLotLFGKmr4Xz0_qEKGI-rxiv4k=
KIzGnBRcU7oSrRtJKXVdnatuVTg1xZBVB12HVNhyNvYKq6Ccyn5tssynSMicD8lCZsLGofaMwoP=
-fxzwIbrs8gXz_kuh3e0TWgh3FF-4qh1--japjR4x3MDkC31S6HqbmStXhFZHNSyVu1YJlsQ97y=
_9A_PY2TdQ]
Since the Financial Crisis in 2009, that=E2=80=99s mostly flipped. Today, t=
he risk-free rate is at 1.29% while inflation is at 4.31% (based on the Con=
sumer Price Index, whether that=E2=80=99s accurately capturing real inflati=
on is for another conversation). That means that if you invest in 10 Year T=
reasuries, your money buys 3% less every year.=C2=A0
Oaktree=E2=80=99s Howard Marks wrote an excellent memo on this topic back i=
n October titled Coming Into Focus [https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkc=
2OrCAQRp-m2bVBUGgWLGZzX8PwU9qkFQwU1_j2g-1iEkIl9VE5lYMzCEvKp95TQXJdE5476AhHW=
QERMqkF8hS87gV78XFQxOvB96_xRUKZ5gywmbBqzBXIXu0anMGQ4neCUjaSt54tCDlSq5waxEsw=
7wbFuLdUCcmo5TfXVB8gOtDwH_KZIpBVvxH38uA_D_avneM4umQ-2JjO7AHN2rm0tcAnV64Cs6k=
rPkuq2UFrbLClK2ivQlyeIWJ6zsnV0u1-JkEzynoqmerZKDjt-k54Ieg8AlVeGdNLkHKUYOlo5l=
7Oxj0Gui2sK9UWNO5z4UnWMaFNuRFa_HmbDb57XTamVrcaA54TRGNX8LcovH1_1U0LRMjtH_xk8=
LIs2zIDVXxgt5hmkit-qWekkX1qU_EP-gsRzpiE]. If you want to go deep, you shoul=
d read the whole thing. The takeaway is that lower interest rates have a dr=
amatic impact on every part of the market. When the risk-free rate is lower=
, returns on all other asset classes come down, too.
Source: Howard Marks, Oaktree
To generate the same returns you were used to at a higher risk-free rate, y=
ou need to take on more risk. This is one of the reasons so much money has =
flowed into growth equities and venture capital since the Fed lowered rates=
 in response to COVID.=C2=A0
Long story short, bonds should not be 40% of your portfolio unless you have=
 a strong thesis for why they should be.=C2=A0
There=E2=80=99s alpha in the private markets if you pick the right managers=
 and strategies.
The difference between the 25th and 75th percentile managers in funds focus=
ed on traditional, publicly available assets like US Fixed Income or US Lar=
ge Cap Equities is tiny. You=E2=80=99re probably better off avoiding paying=
 the fees and just buying an index.=C2=A0
Source: KKR [https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxNkc-OhCAMxp9muGkAReXAYS_7G=
oY_VckgGKhr5u0XZw67CYG0pf2-_Go1wprySx2pILmvGV8HqAhXCYAImZwF8uydYgOfOtFL4lTv=
2CQm4su8ZIBd-6Awn0CO0wRvNfoU3x2UckE2RTvG5Gik1bAMgxD9JDuzwMCYnZwzy0dXn85DtKD=
gB_IrRSBBbYhHeXRfD_5dz3Vd7fOZW5v2Gq0hGR2aA3I5wKL_gVKz_yzc4Rkw62bz69ZEwOZKGb=
fGx_oXU27qIB_XRq9AvOKUMzpyybgYOtqydnDDQBcBVDqpNRthHMUIhgq9sHHR9tHTfeVtOU1Bb=
Z-3LZJVTGhSrmNr-bnpHcK7UH3N9d3P6PE1Q9QmgPtQww_8N8d5hQi5LsXNGm_kYzXTU9n1_EOp=
Yu1kd--Bk6rsUu2Kf6K_w5Kerg]
BUT, and this is one of the tropes that Tory wants to kill, that doesn=E2=
=80=99t mean that all hedge funds underperform the market after they take t=
heir fees. That=E2=80=99s become a popular narrative, and when you look at =
it in the aggregate, it looks true, but there is a huge variance in perform=
ance between top and bottom managers in private, alternative asset classes =
like Venture Capital, Real Estate, Growth Equity, Private Equity, Private C=
redit, and more.=C2=A0
That means that you should be able to generate above-average risk-adjusted =
returns if you can pick, and allocate to, the best managers across a divers=
ified portfolio of non-correlated strategies.=C2=A0
